00:10:31.640 --> 00:10:36.140
this will be a day which, of
course, I will never forget.

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:42.020
But, I would like to thank all of
you for braving the cold weather,

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:45.620
and the traffic I have to say,
and come here this evening.

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:47.010
Thank you very much.

00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:52.230
I'm going to start reading
a poem, given that a couple

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:54.550
of days ago it was
St. Valentine's day,

00:10:54.550 --> 00:11:01.130
which it seems is being
celebrated, how should I say,

00:11:01.130 --> 00:11:04.340
quite regularly now
year in, year out.

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:08.430
It's a love poem divided
into different pieces.

00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:14.540
When you dress in black
you spread the night

00:11:14.540 --> 00:11:19.170
over your breast, and
hide the full moon.

00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:25.520
Which, however, comes out
to peep through your eyes.

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:30.210
Your hair pulled back is
a wind that doesn't steer.

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:34.340
Your hands are folded in a caress.

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:36.920
You're thinking that
tomorrow the sea will rise

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:39.810
to take you, you don't know where.

00:11:39.810 --> 00:11:48.230
Maybe it will take you where eyes
have never seen, ears never heard.

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:53.230
Your fingers grasp the leaf
you spread the dream on,

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.220
which was born once
while you were sailing

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:58.930
with your loved one still
hidden in your embrace.

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:06.420
Your eyes read the horizon he
painted for you, the hidden one

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:10.510
who loves you in the
depths of your breast.

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:15.740
Your eyes wish to cry in the
middle of a smile as soon

00:12:15.740 --> 00:12:20.220
as you finish reading the poem.

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:26.660
Your lips are a long night
which scarcely wants to end,

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:29.310
dreaming with the movement
of violence

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:33.740
on boundless expanses
of green grass.

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:38.400
A blue night, which turns
silently melancholic,

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:43.620
lost among large expanses
of white sheets.

00:12:43.620 --> 00:12:49.250
Your lips are the small
island which is drowning.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:53.720
Slowly the water rises, sweetly.

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:57.910
This drowning becomes
sacred as it ends.

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:02.150
Its very peaks are
covered by the blue sea,

00:13:02.150 --> 00:13:06.600
the island which is lost in memory.

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:10.940
Your lips are the stillness
falling slowly, slowly.

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:13.970
Soon they'll be heard crying.

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:17.260
They'll soon be silent.

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:23.440
When you come down to
lie on the sea's surface

00:13:23.440 --> 00:13:28.830
and you forget the corners
one by one because you wish

00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:31.610
to get quickly to the sand.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:35.480
You wish to hear your
own voice reply

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:39.100
to the call you throw
to the restless sea.

00:13:39.100 --> 00:13:41.740
When you come down to lie

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:45.340
on the sea's surface your
face touches its face,

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:50.490
its body your body, while
you fly far away in order

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:55.180
to forget these corners
which have risen one by one,

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:58.120
people's unintentional
bumping into you.

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:02.110
You wish alone to approach the
sand where your clothes fall

00:14:02.110 --> 00:14:08.210 position:56%
in a heap while you still walk,
nude as the sea, as is this silence,

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:11.940
this bay which has
hidden in early morning.

00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:14.990
You wish to forget, to feel alone.

00:14:14.990 --> 00:14:20.270
You wish to sleep to the naked
sound of water rising on you.

00:14:20.270 --> 00:14:24.950
You wish to sleep,
to dream, of silence.

00:14:24.950 --> 00:14:30.310
And then you look at the
earth with shut eyes,

00:14:30.310 --> 00:14:36.430
and see black pictures
coming towards you.

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:39.400
Of course that was a translation,

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:44.580
and all the poems I will be reading
were originally written in Maltese.

00:14:44.580 --> 00:14:50.830 position:56%
I would like to thank my translators
for making it possible that I read

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.820
to people who do not
understand my language.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:59.260
Speaking of my language, I would
like to read just a snippet

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:06.090
in Maltese so that you
will hear the language.

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:08.550
So, this is just the beginning

00:15:08.550 --> 00:15:13.310
of a poem I shall be reading
right after this excerpt.

00:15:13.310 --> 00:15:20.510
It is called Macedonia Square, the
main square in Skopje, Macedonia.

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:58.270
[reading in Maltese]

00:15:58.270 --> 00:16:03.490
&gt;&gt; So, that was Maltese.

00:16:03.490 --> 00:16:09.170
Now the same poem, but the whole
lot in English translation.

00:16:12.930 --> 00:16:15.740
Macedonia Square.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:24.420
I always meet you, you spirits of
old cities, ghosts playing violins,

00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:31.540
the same songs old and
dim, always about loves

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:34.040
that have tried and failed.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:40.100
Always the same death in
the middle of the square.

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:44.290
By now I'm used to having you
appear out of nowhere to bestow

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:47.280
on me your solitary welcome.

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:52.360
Strings, destined to play
only images familiar,

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:57.390
like the same sweaty embrace,
and tears of silver dropping

00:16:57.390 --> 00:17:00.880
on our lapels and running
everywhere.

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:05.250
It's raining, but you keep
on rambling through streets

00:17:05.250 --> 00:17:10.840 position:56%
that are bursting with lore of kings
and queens, who sketched a map that,

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:14.580
silently, we can't help but follow.

00:17:16.070 --> 00:17:23.870
Just for tonight, we shall sit at
table, smoke a cigarette together,

00:17:23.870 --> 00:17:30.040
and then we'll cry, and feel the
tears give us pleasure only we two

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:31.660
can understand.

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:39.740
Because there is no one else
left in this old city like us.

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:48.700
[pause]

00:17:48.700 --> 00:17:53.040
&gt;&gt; Since I came here
I forgot my name.

00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:56.530
I slept in seven different beds,

00:17:56.530 --> 00:18:01.630
climbed up mountain tops,
dipped my feet in lakes.

00:18:01.630 --> 00:18:07.560 position:56%
I spoke some four languages I didn't
know, browned in the blazing sun,

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:11.110
froze under the biting hail.

00:18:11.110 --> 00:18:13.760
I met people whose
name I never learned,

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:18.300
I ate and drank all they gave
me and heard their stories

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:20.800
and those of their ancestors.

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:23.810
I rode cars of every
shape and color.

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:28.510
And then they drove
me to the city's end.

00:18:28.510 --> 00:18:33.800
I asked them where I
was, but no one answered.

00:18:37.140 --> 00:18:40.320
This is another poem from Skopje.

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:47.140
And rain starts falling
heavily again.

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:51.800
Again, that song we heard six
months ago when we were alone,

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:54.460
looking shyly at each other,

00:18:54.460 --> 00:18:58.920
undecided whether to
make love or not.

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:03.580
And then you said, "Better not,
because tomorrow you're leaving."

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:07.110
Then you cried, and I stared,

00:19:07.110 --> 00:19:11.870
lost my eyes along the
edges of your hair.

00:19:11.870 --> 00:19:16.730
Again, that stuffy weather
and humid, dropping loads

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:20.210
of leaves before they died,

00:19:20.210 --> 00:19:24.030
and again that song
we heard six years ago

00:19:24.030 --> 00:19:29.000 position:56%
when we were alone together, looking
with nostalgia at each other,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:34.010
and decided what should or next
words be after, "How's it going?

00:19:34.010 --> 00:19:35.830
It's been ages."

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:41.940
And after a few uneasy seconds
I spot the strange marks,

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:45.190
sad and silent, that
the rain left scattered

00:19:45.190 --> 00:19:48.560
in the corners of your face.

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:53.620
Against your wishes you have to
tell me again, "Hurry, run now.

00:19:53.620 --> 00:19:56.190
The plane is waiting."

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:59.400
Everywhere I go I seem
to find someone waiting.

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:03.630
If it's not the plane then it's
a strong gust of wind rising up

00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:07.300
and pouncing from behind every
corner, with tearful eyes,

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:10.460
with sure marks of aging.

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:14.660
I look up, and the lights
turn to green again.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:22.740
I would like to read two
poems about my mother.

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:27.400
My mother was a very
religious person,

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:29.770
and when you say a
very religious person

00:20:29.770 --> 00:20:34.600
in Malta, it means very Catholic.

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:38.060
The first poem I'm going to read,

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:41.460
I was told that this ritual is
no longer allowed in churches,

00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:47.450
but up to a few years
ago, right after the end,

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:52.110
or just before the end of
the mass, before internment,

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:58.870
relatives could go and read
a message or something.

00:20:58.870 --> 00:21:04.880
And when my mother died, which
was on the eve of Christmas,

00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:09.430
one of my nieces read this poem,

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:12.870
which I wrote specifically
for my mother's funeral.

00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:18.500
I have to tell you, it's never
been read, not even in Maltese,

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:23.570
except on that particular day,
so this is really a premier,

00:21:23.570 --> 00:21:27.580
because I've never read
this poem in public before.

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:31.570
It's called of course,
A Poem for Your Funeral.

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:39.770
Mom, I remember you sitting out in
the yard peeling tangerines for me,

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:44.980
and telling the lovely stories
which you always knew how to weave.

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:48.290
And Mom, I remember
you telling me once

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:52.610
that you'd seen the stars fall
one by one, and there were

00:21:52.610 --> 00:21:57.000
so many that the sea lit up.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.460
Before I went to bed
you always told me

00:21:59.460 --> 00:22:03.610
that the rain was only
Our Lady's needles.

00:22:03.610 --> 00:22:07.970
If you touched them they
wouldn't prick, as they were holy.

00:22:07.970 --> 00:22:13.550
The wind was nothing but the voice
of God singing, and the lightning

00:22:13.550 --> 00:22:19.090
and the thunder were the toys which
Jesus dropped while he was playing.

00:22:19.090 --> 00:22:21.230
I remember you, Mom.

00:22:21.230 --> 00:22:27.890
Beautiful as red roses, as orange
