When I dozed off, I dreamt of
voices I used to hear often,

00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:17.880
wafting through lush tree branches.

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:25.320
I dreamt of the voices of old folks
I knew, maundering on for hours.

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:30.690
I dreamt of the voices
of apples, ripe melons,

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:34.990
of milk sauntering freely
through my mother's full breast,

00:42:34.990 --> 00:42:40.300
and spicy voices rising from
Latakia leaves, pungent,

00:42:40.300 --> 00:42:43.740
being smoked by olive dark men.

00:42:43.740 --> 00:42:50.410
Then I dreamt again,
of sweat, and of bones,

00:42:50.410 --> 00:42:56.590
of cold black holes piercing
me, pleading me, "Don't go!"

00:42:56.590 --> 00:43:00.960
Telling me to turn back,
"get away from the shore,

00:43:00.960 --> 00:43:05.170
pay no attention to men with boats.

00:43:05.170 --> 00:43:10.170
Beware the water,"
they say, "It's cruel."

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:15.730
The voices cry out
danger, warning me sure,

00:43:15.730 --> 00:43:20.560
"Don't step on another man's land."

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:23.240
I woke with a jolt.

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:30.620
And so before me descends a blue
carpet unfurling to that cold land,

00:43:30.620 --> 00:43:34.940
a land that's afraid of,
yet doesn't even know me,

00:43:34.940 --> 00:43:38.580
a land that I'm no less
determined to set foot on,

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:42.360
so I walk on towards the boats.

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:44.930 position:56%
I carry this bag that I have chosen,

00:43:44.930 --> 00:43:49.190
packed it with my whole
story, one bag.

00:43:49.190 --> 00:43:55.990 position:56%
And even that will soon get
lighter once, at gun or knife point,

00:43:55.990 --> 00:44:00.010
I pay my passage to climb
into their sea craft,

00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:04.220
challenging voices
urging me to stop.

00:44:04.220 --> 00:44:05.660
Will the boat make it?

00:44:05.660 --> 00:44:13.070
Will it? Once upon a shore
there were children playing,

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:16.680
chasing a ball, running
and laughing.

00:44:16.680 --> 00:44:21.140
Someone from afar, someone
from afar gunned them down,

00:44:21.140 --> 00:44:24.050
and there was no one left
on the beach save the ball,

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:25.710
which stood there waiting.

00:44:25.710 --> 00:44:29.370
I remember that ball
bouncing across and back sand.

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:33.640
I remember my cousins laughing,
running, the ball bouncing,

00:44:33.640 --> 00:44:37.920
speeding faster than us, then
the wind joined in playing

00:44:37.920 --> 00:44:41.080
with the ball, and it
started playing with us.

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:44.130
We were trying our best
to outrun that wind,

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:46.650
reach the ball it had
cruelly snatched,

00:44:46.650 --> 00:44:49.230
racing to see who might
get it first.

00:44:49.230 --> 00:44:51.280
Of course I was the last.

00:44:51.280 --> 00:44:52.990
I ran the slowest.

00:44:52.990 --> 00:44:54.760
I couldn't beat the wind.

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:57.660
But I ran, I ran, we all did!

00:44:57.660 --> 00:45:01.700
The taunt of the wind, the
sound of laughter, and then,

00:45:01.700 --> 00:45:06.670 position:56%
then someone from afar, someone from
afar gunned us down, and no one,

00:45:06.670 --> 00:45:09.450
not one of us reached the ball.

00:45:09.450 --> 00:45:12.820
Still the wind stayed
on, having already won,

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:15.910
kept playing on its
own, but with my face

00:45:15.910 --> 00:45:20.650
to the ground I see nothing
at all, only darkness.

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:28.960
Now I have no idea how long
I've been here waiting.

00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:31.210
A day, two, three?

00:45:31.210 --> 00:45:34.510
More? I wait.

00:45:34.510 --> 00:45:37.150
Locked up with strangers
locked up with me.

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:43.030
And we look, and we look at the
dark blue sea, and we count.

00:45:43.030 --> 00:45:48.410
Counting every strange, and
very strange numbers of, sounds,

00:45:48.410 --> 00:45:51.640
bank notes for the guy
with the Kalashnikov,

00:45:51.640 --> 00:45:57.110
steps we take wasted deep
into the water to get

00:45:57.110 --> 00:46:01.640
to this fragile boat
meant to transport us,

00:46:01.640 --> 00:46:05.960
and I see that my bag is
swelling with the sea.

00:46:05.960 --> 00:46:10.030
My passport inside,
close to tatters.

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:13.960
Faces of my loved ones
now drifting in water,

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:18.270
my pills one by one
melting and dropping.

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:23.470
My dates have lost their
sweetness, quickly turning salty.

00:46:23.470 --> 00:46:28.980
The jacket and the jersey
threadbare, I lose all my story.

00:46:28.980 --> 00:46:33.830
Now drenched, watch it dissolving.

00:46:33.830 --> 00:46:40.390
Like caught fish packed in
crates, we set off for the unknown.

00:46:40.390 --> 00:46:44.230
Behind me, ashore with damp sands,

00:46:44.230 --> 00:46:47.700
there's no one left
there save a gust of wind

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:53.950 position:56%
and heavy silence you always hear as
you close one book to open another.

00:46:53.950 --> 00:47:00.990
There is a curious white
blot, and it's spreading,

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:05.240
carried neither by
wind nor by water.

00:47:05.240 --> 00:47:10.010
But I can see clearly, there's
a child in a red top face

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:16.140
down kissing the sand, washed by
the sea, a cleansing for burial.

00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:21.590
And the wind begins to blow as
it always does when it wakes,

00:47:21.590 --> 00:47:25.860
but the red-shirted
child does not stir.

00:47:25.860 --> 00:47:30.680
And the boat carries
us off now, away, away.

00:47:30.680 --> 00:47:35.630
Maybe we'll get there, maybe.

00:47:35.630 --> 00:47:39.040
And we ask, will this boat make it?

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:43.880
Will it? Or will it
lose breath, seizing,

00:47:43.880 --> 00:47:47.610
just before the sea stops, and ...

00:47:47.610 --> 00:47:54.020
The waves, the sand, mountainous,
crushing, screams, darkness, cold,

00:47:54.020 --> 00:48:01.580
thirst, cries, and suddenly ...

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:16.860
Thank you very much.

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:18.160
[applause]

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:23.170
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: So, we will watch
a video, a beautiful video,

00:48:23.170 --> 00:48:29.090
produced in the Czech Republic
with Dr. Mifsud as a protagonist

00:48:29.090 --> 00:48:32.570
in it, on the sea, in a boat.

00:48:32.570 --> 00:48:33.930
I won't say more.

00:48:33.930 --> 00:48:39.240
We will give Dr. Mifsud some
time to transition into a part

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:42.330
of our program which
is a conversation,

00:48:42.330 --> 00:49:34.830
a briefer conversation, but a
conversation between the two of us.

00:49:34.830 --> 00:50:17.980
Thank you.

00:50:17.980 --> 00:56:11.090
[video]

00:56:11.090 --> 00:56:14.350
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: I would like
to take advantage of the fact

00:56:14.350 --> 00:56:19.410
that you're here, and have you
read also a couple of passages

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:24.780
from In The Name of the
Father, rather than me doing it.

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:26.080
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Sure.

00:56:26.080 --> 00:56:27.380
Right.

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:28.680 position:56%
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: Because it is
inherent to a question that I wanted

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:32.790
to ask you, which is
very much tied to a video

00:56:32.790 --> 00:56:40.090
that we have just seen, The Sea.

00:56:40.090 --> 00:56:45.840
Starting to, when you
get home, you collapse.

00:56:45.840 --> 00:56:48.610
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: To?

00:56:48.610 --> 00:56:53.240
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: To The Tower,
"I'm afraid of a lot of things."

00:56:53.240 --> 00:56:56.510
"I'm afraid of a lot of things" ...

00:56:56.510 --> 00:56:58.830
Yes, "I'm afraid of
a lot of things".

00:56:58.830 --> 00:57:00.440
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Yes.

00:57:00.440 --> 00:57:03.670
When you get home you
collapse onto the nearest chair

00:57:03.670 --> 00:57:06.060
and then lace your boots.

00:57:06.060 --> 00:57:10.370
You always unlace the left
boot first, and you ask me

00:57:10.370 --> 00:57:13.220
to pull your boots off for you.

00:57:13.220 --> 00:57:17.820
Once they're off, they feel heavy
in my hands, and you tell me

00:57:17.820 --> 00:57:20.630
to line them up neatly
under the bed.

00:57:20.630 --> 00:57:26.100
And you roll along like
a boat on a rough sea.

00:57:26.100 --> 00:57:30.290
And the sea gets rougher
once your boots are off.

00:57:30.290 --> 00:57:34.940
No shortness of breath in spite
of all the cigarettes you smoke.

00:57:34.940 --> 00:57:40.660
You dive to the very bottom of
the bay below [inaudible] to bring

00:57:40.660 --> 00:57:45.510
up sea urchins, scores of sea
urchins in the wicker basket.

00:57:45.510 --> 00:57:49.480
They reek of the sea.

00:57:49.480 --> 00:57:53.440
The smell of sea urchins is
alien to me, and I've never been

00:57:53.440 --> 00:58:01.520
down to [inaudible], and
those dark depths scare me.

00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:02.820
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: Beautiful.

00:58:02.820 --> 00:58:08.020
I have another passage related
to the question we are going to,

00:58:08.020 --> 00:58:16.270
and this time it is about the
