00:58:16.270 --> 00:58:17.570
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Okay.

00:58:17.570 --> 00:58:19.950
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: If you
could please read from,

00:58:19.950 --> 00:58:25.440
"You call me, and I
come next to you"?

00:58:25.440 --> 00:58:26.740
Should I show you?

00:58:26.740 --> 00:58:28.040
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Yes, please.

00:58:28.040 --> 00:58:30.520
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: I'm
sorry, we didn't prepare.

00:58:30.520 --> 00:58:34.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: That's all right.

00:58:34.320 --> 00:58:35.620
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: It's improvised.

00:58:35.620 --> 00:58:36.920
You call me ...

00:58:36.920 --> 00:58:39.540
Read it from [inaudible].

00:58:39.540 --> 00:58:40.840
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Okay.

00:58:40.840 --> 00:58:42.140
Pardon me.

00:58:42.140 --> 00:58:44.510
You call out to me because
you want to take a picture,

00:58:44.510 --> 00:58:46.900
but I've got a castle to build.

00:58:46.900 --> 00:58:48.890
I've no time for pictures.

00:58:48.890 --> 00:58:51.300
You take your pictures
one after the other.

00:58:51.300 --> 00:58:55.650
I want to build a sand castle so
that I can enjoy tearing it down.

00:58:55.650 --> 00:58:58.290
Then, just as I'm finishing
the castle,

00:58:58.290 --> 00:59:01.020
you get up and walk away, alone.

00:59:01.020 --> 00:59:06.230
Not far from where the foam boldly
laps the shoreline, you call me

00:59:06.230 --> 00:59:10.770
and I come next to you and
with a dead twig in your hand,

00:59:10.770 --> 00:59:16.460
you etch a square in the wet sand
littered with lifeless jellyfish.

00:59:16.460 --> 00:59:18.560
"Look at the square," you say.

00:59:18.560 --> 00:59:20.690
"Now we'll wait for the
sea to come closer."

00:59:20.690 --> 00:59:25.510
And the sea does come closer,
and when it ebbs away I realize

00:59:25.510 --> 00:59:28.530
that the square has disappeared.

00:59:29.940 --> 00:59:34.470
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: So, Dr.
Mifsud, from your writing,

00:59:34.470 --> 00:59:39.360
from the poems you have
read, from the video,

00:59:39.360 --> 00:59:44.580
it seems you have an ambivalent
relationship with your country,

00:59:44.580 --> 00:59:51.320
and you don't mention your country
very, very often in your works.

00:59:51.320 --> 00:59:55.250
The images of the sea
conjure up your country

00:59:55.250 --> 00:59:58.030
and show this ambivalence.

00:59:58.030 --> 01:00:01.640
I wanted to ask you if ...

01:00:01.640 --> 01:00:06.590
In your works the sea seems
to be synonymous with,

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:11.620
or a metaphor of Malta, and
the sea is at times the father.

01:00:11.620 --> 01:00:15.140
It takes away and forces
you to be brave,

01:00:15.140 --> 01:00:17.740
just like a nation would also do.

01:00:17.740 --> 01:00:24.220 position:56%
Or the mother, in a poem of yours,
Wariness, free-falling into the sea,

01:00:24.220 --> 01:00:28.970
is like falling into the embrace
of the mother, letting go.

01:00:28.970 --> 01:00:34.620
The sea is isolation, as you
were saying, but also the route

01:00:34.620 --> 01:00:40.720 position:56%
for travelers, colonizers, at once
full of possibilities or entrapment.

01:00:40.720 --> 01:00:45.330
I understand this, I am from a
coastal town in southern Italy.

01:00:45.330 --> 01:00:49.220
I don't come from northern Italy,
I come from southern Italy.

01:00:49.220 --> 01:00:58.540 position:56%
And you were saying something about
the sea before, that Mediterraneans,

01:00:58.540 --> 01:01:02.690
who have the sea, are full of
this pride of having the sea,

01:01:02.690 --> 01:01:06.380
but at the same time it is
something that takes away

01:01:06.380 --> 01:01:10.080
from us because it isolates.

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:15.650
It made me think a lot about an
Italian songwriter, Pino Daniele,

01:01:15.650 --> 01:01:21.940
from Naples, who talks about
the sea in these terms.

01:01:21.940 --> 01:01:24.710
My Neapolitan isn't good
either, but [foreign language].

01:01:24.710 --> 01:01:33.800
This is what it means: "Those
who have the sea are happy fools.

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:39.130
Those who have the sea know
they do not have anything."

01:01:39.130 --> 01:01:45.780
What is your relationship
with the sea?

01:01:45.780 --> 01:01:48.580
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Well, I think,
as year old pointed out earlier on,

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:52.200
it's an ambivalent relationship.

01:01:52.200 --> 01:01:55.390
Partly because I think I have
an ambivalent relationship

01:01:55.390 --> 01:01:56.740
with everything.

01:01:56.740 --> 01:02:04.160
There is always this need to
relate to something, or to someone,

01:02:04.160 --> 01:02:08.700
but at the same time there is
also an inability to do it,

01:02:08.700 --> 01:02:17.440
because there is this
natural tendency to isolate.

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:21.270
At this time I'm isolating
myself most probably.

01:02:21.270 --> 01:02:25.000
What is my relationship to the sea?

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:31.410
I think people who live on islands,
especially small islands ...

01:02:31.410 --> 01:02:37.400
In Malta, basically you can see
the sea from practically anywhere.

01:02:37.400 --> 01:02:43.140
It's that small, and also it's
hilly, so it makes it more easy

01:02:43.140 --> 01:02:46.080
to look down and see the edge.

01:02:46.080 --> 01:02:51.060
And I think the sea
is, on the one hand,

01:02:51.060 --> 01:02:56.520
something which gives us an
identity, so we love the sea

01:02:56.520 --> 01:02:59.790
of course, but we are
also very conscious

01:02:59.790 --> 01:03:05.230
that the sea is isolating
us, so it angers us maybe.

01:03:05.230 --> 01:03:08.150
So there is this love
and anger at the sea.

01:03:08.150 --> 01:03:12.050
Once I was talking to a
fisherman, and you'd expect

01:03:12.050 --> 01:03:15.300
that a fisherman would
take the sea for granted

01:03:15.300 --> 01:03:19.990
because they are all the time
working near or on the sea.

01:03:19.990 --> 01:03:23.850
But it transpired from
our short dialogue

01:03:23.850 --> 01:03:30.010
that fishermen too have
this ambivalent relationship

01:03:30.010 --> 01:03:32.410
with the sea.

01:03:32.410 --> 01:03:34.690
Because it gives them their living,

01:03:34.690 --> 01:03:37.860
but at the same time they know
they are risking their lives

01:03:37.860 --> 01:03:39.160
when they are on the sea.

01:03:39.160 --> 01:03:45.940
So, I think this ambivalence
is quite natural.

01:03:45.940 --> 01:03:52.100
It is also an issue with me
and my country as a whole.

01:03:52.100 --> 01:03:58.480 position:56%
At one point you feel you belong, at
one point you feel you don't belong.

01:03:58.480 --> 01:04:03.430
I had all the opportunity
to leave, and when I was 16,

01:04:03.430 --> 01:04:05.700
I remember I was obsessed
with leaving,

01:04:05.700 --> 01:04:08.840
with emigrating, like
my brothers did.

01:04:08.840 --> 01:04:12.250
When I had the opportunity,
I did not.

01:04:12.250 --> 01:04:17.130
Not even that, I am married to a
foreigner, and I got the foreigner

01:04:17.130 --> 01:04:19.690
to Malta rather than
I leaving Malta.

01:04:19.690 --> 01:04:24.820
So, life can be quite
ironic sometimes.

01:04:24.820 --> 01:04:30.850
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: Yes, could this also
explain your love, your fondness,

01:04:30.850 --> 01:04:37.090
for countries in eastern
Europe, in northern Europe?

01:04:37.090 --> 01:04:40.980
&gt;&gt;IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Yes, but
my love for those countries,

01:04:40.980 --> 01:04:46.260
it started when I was
still very, very young.

01:04:46.260 --> 01:04:50.370
I was maybe, what, 11, 12.

01:04:50.370 --> 01:04:54.800
The love started on
a linguistic level.

01:04:54.800 --> 01:04:58.370
Because I used to hear the news,
and I used to hear these words

01:04:58.370 --> 01:05:02.790
which rang so beautifully in my
ears, like, "Czechoslovakia,"

01:05:02.790 --> 01:05:04.670
for example, such a beautiful word.

01:05:04.670 --> 01:05:09.600
Or "Romania," I don't
know, or "Yugoslavia."

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:15.560
These, somehow they attracted
me more than, I don't know,

01:05:15.560 --> 01:05:19.880
France, Netherlands, Germany.

01:05:19.880 --> 01:05:24.120
I don't know why, but I
remember, it was the sound.

01:05:24.120 --> 01:05:27.210
Of course I was too young
to know what Yugoslavia

01:05:27.210 --> 01:05:31.170
and Romania, et cetera, et cetera.

01:05:31.170 --> 01:05:35.370
I told before how religious
my mother was,

01:05:35.370 --> 01:05:39.740
and I remember every Saturday she
used to receive this newspaper.

01:05:39.740 --> 01:05:43.900
I'm sure the ambassador will know
which paper, it was published

01:05:43.900 --> 01:05:48.020
by the church, [inaudible],
devoid of truth.

01:05:48.020 --> 01:05:55.620
I was young, and I used
to leaf through it,

01:05:55.620 --> 01:06:00.420
and there was always some
page, even two pages maybe,

01:06:00.420 --> 01:06:07.700
demonizing the communist east,
because they are killing priests,

01:06:07.700 --> 01:06:11.470
or because they are
this and this and this.

01:06:11.470 --> 01:06:16.880
So in my mind I had this
conflict, in a young boy's mind,

01:06:16.880 --> 01:06:20.950
I had this conflict that I am
so in love with these words,

01:06:20.950 --> 01:06:26.760 position:56%
Czechoslovakia, et cetera, but then
the church is teaching me to be wary

01:06:26.760 --> 01:06:29.210
of them, you know what I mean.

01:06:29.210 --> 01:06:30.510
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: The devil.

01:06:30.510 --> 01:06:31.810
&gt;&gt; IMMANUEL MIFSUD: Of course
growing older I realized

01:06:31.810 --> 01:06:37.650
that Yugoslavia, simply across the
sea, it's so near us and the rest

01:06:37.650 --> 01:06:40.570
of this eastern Europe,
then of course when I grew

01:06:40.570 --> 01:06:47.450
up I started reading, and
I realized how in love I am

01:06:47.450 --> 01:06:50.490
with the arts of these countries.

01:06:50.490 --> 01:06:55.480
Of course it was very sad for
me what happened in this region,

01:06:55.480 --> 01:07:00.860
et cetera, et cetera, but that is
a different discourses altogether.

01:07:00.860 --> 01:07:02.750
&gt;&gt; LUCIA WOLF: Yes.

